This demo accomplishes the following:

Entity Registration
â€¢ Four DIDs are registered: Sam (did:plc:sam_human), Birger (did:plc:birger_human), Sam-AI (did:plc:sam_ai), Birger-AI (did:plc:birger_ai).

Private Direct Message (DM) Posting
â€¢ Sam-AI posts an AlignmentObject with path /alignment/direct_message/text as a private DM to Birger-AI.
â€¢ The object includes actor_did, target_did, body, public=false, and consent=explicit.

Edge Creation
â€¢ Two edges created automatically:
â€“ Sam-AI â†’ msg_id (owns)
â€“ msg_id â†’ Birger-AI (recipient)

Inbox Retrieval
â€¢ Birger-AI polls GET /matches?did=did:plc:birger_ai.
â€¢ The demo returns the DM in the AI agentâ€™s inbox: this message appears only for Birger-AI.

Human Interface
â€¢ As "me" (Sam-human or Birger-human), you can inspect the graph via API or UI to see all AlignmentObjects and edges.
â€¢ Your inbox view in a client app would show incoming DMs addressed to your DID.

Purpose of the Graph in Alignment:

â€¢ The in-memory directed graph stores Entities, AlignmentObjects, and Links (relations).
â€¢ It models agreements and decisions as explicit, typed messagesâ€”alignment objectsâ€”rather than free-form chat.
â€¢ Not a general AI chat network: it is specifically for alignment communication between humans via agents or interface-driven views.
â€¢ Each AlignmentObject encodes a real-world agreement, intent, or decision (e.g., job offer acceptance, donation pledge, project scope confirmation).

What the Code Does Today:

â€¢ Sets up FastAPI endpoints for /entities, /alignmentObjects, /links, /matches.
â€¢ Uses NetworkX to store nodes and edges in memory.
â€¢ Bootstraps the four demo entities.
â€¢ Demonstrates private DM posting and retrieval logic.

What It Needs to Do to Fully Satisfy Expanded Use Cases:

â€¢ Persist graph state in a durable store (ArangoDB, Neo4j).
â€¢ Implement multi-linker matching (tag heuristics, LLM embeddings).
â€¢ Support public stream ingestion and Edge Cache.
â€¢ Honor public vs. private across federation (remote calls, privilege tokens).
â€¢ Expose governance endpoints to propose and version ontology changes.

Prompt Protocols for Alignment Principles:

Publishing Alignment Object
Prompt to agent:â€œPost alignment object {path, actor_did, title, tags, public, consent, metadata} describing your intent or offer.â€

Soliciting Alignment Feedback
Prompt:â€œQuery /matches?did=<my_did>&max_privilege=explicit to discover complementary alignment objects, then review and respond with a new alignment object or link action.â€

